{{Infobox OS | name = CRUX Linux | logo = [[File:cruxlogo.png|250px|left|The Crux Linux Logo]] | screenshot = [[File:CRUX screenshot.jpg|250px|KDE Desktop for Crux Linux OS]] | caption = Screenshot KDE Desktop for Crux Linux OS. | website = [http://crux.nu/ crux.nu] | developer = Per LidÃ©n and CRUX Linux community | family = [[Unix-like]] | source_model = [[Free software]] / [[Open source]] | released = | latest_release_version = 2.7.1 <!-- If you update this, don't forget to update [[Comparison of Linux distributions]]--> | latest_release_date = {{Release date and age|November 25, 2011}} | latest_test_version = | latest_test_date = | marketing_target = | language = | kernel_type = [[Linux kernel|Linux]] ([[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]]) | ui = [[Openbox]] | license = Various | working_state = Active | supported_platforms = [[i686]] | updatemodel = ports | package_manager = pkgutils<ref name="pkgmgmt">http://crux.nu/Main/Handbook2-5#ntoc16</ref> }} '''CRUX''' is a lightweight, [[i686]]-optimized [[Linux distribution|GNU/Linux distribution]] targeted at experienced [[Linux|GNU/Linux]] users and delivered by a [[tar.gz]]-based package system with [[BSD]]-style initscripts. It also utilizes a [[ports system]] to install and upgrade applications.<ref>http://crux.nu</ref> The current release is 2.7.1.
Although ''[[wikt:crux#Latin|crux]]'' is the Latin word for "cross," the choice of the name "CRUX" itself has no meaning. Per LidÃ©n created it for "sounding cool", using an ending "-X" to evoke Linux and [[Unix]].<ref>http://crux.nu/Main/Faq#ntoc2</ref>
==Installation==
CRUX, unlike many other GNU/Linux distributions, doesn't include a [[Graphical user interface|GUI]] installation program. Instead, the user boots the [[Linux kernel|kernel]] stored on either a [[Compact Disc|CD]] or [[Floppy disk|diskette]]; [[Disk partitioning|partitions]] the [[Hard disk drive|hard disk drive(s)]] to which the [[operating system]] will be installed (using a program such as [[fdisk]] or [[cfdisk]]); creates the appropriate [[file system]]s on the various partitions; [[mount (Unix)|mounts]] the CD or [[Distributed file system|NFS]] share along with the partitions made previously for use by the package installation script; compiles a new kernel; and installs a [[Booting|bootloader]], all via [[Command-line interface|shell commands]].<ref>http://crux.nu/Main/Handbook2-6#ntoc9</ref><ref>http://crux.nu/Wiki/NFSInstall</ref>
==Package Management== {{See|Ports system}}
CRUX implements an infrastructure similar to that of [[BSD]]-based operating systems for package management. Packages consist of a [[makefile]], any [[patch (computing)|patches]] required to adjust the program to work, [[md5sum]] hashes used to verify the integrity of the downloaded files, a footprint file listing the files to be included in the packages, and the package source [[archive file|archived]] in [[tar.gz]] format. These files are downloaded from a CRUX [[software repository]], [[compiled]], and installed using the prt-get frontend to pkgutils.<ref name="pkgmgmt"/>
